Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday! Welcome to our 5th Weekly Dose of Optimism, where we celebrat=
e the incredible accomplishments humans manage to pull off and the progress=
 that we=E2=80=99re =E2=80=94 unsteadily and windingly =E2=80=94 making.
It=E2=80=99s been awesome to see the positive response to the Weekly Dose s=
o far. If you=E2=80=99re enjoying it, spread the optimism.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by my daily dose=E2=80=A6 Athletic Greens=
 [https://substack.com/redirect/093911f9-5674-445b-9840-e8cefa543997?u=3D16=
283549]
It=E2=80=99s easier to be optimistic when you start your day right. Every m=
orning, I drink a homemade concoction starring Athletic Greens=E2=80=99 AG1=
 [https://substack.com/redirect/093911f9-5674-445b-9840-e8cefa543997?u=3D16=
283549]. Join me. Not Boring optimists can get a free one-year supply of Vi=
tamin D and 5 travel packs when you order with the special Not Boring link =
[https://substack.com/redirect/bfead327-8c73-4e7b-8146-ad4a1251951d?u=3D162=
83549].
(1) Senate Passes $280 Billion Industrial Policy Bill to Counter China [htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/5ad06ece-834b-4b2e-bfe2-70a42755641d?u=3D1628354=
9]
Catie Edmonson [https://substack.com/redirect/5cae1797-1d80-459f-923c-05f73=
970ca6d?u=3D16283549] for The New York Times
The bill, a convergence of economic and national security policy, would pro=
vide $52 billion in subsidies and additional tax credits to companies that =
manufacture chips in the United States. It also would add $200 billion for =
scientific research, especially into artificial intelligence, robotics, qua=
ntum computing and a variety of other technologies.
Earlier this week, the US Senate passed a $280 billion bill, known as the C=
hips Act, and yesterday, it passed the House 243-187-1, with 24 Republicans=
 joining the party. The bill is a proof point that bipartisanship is still =
possible, and a good example of the point I made Monday: that a common enem=
y can spur action.=20
In this case, the bill is intended to improve America=E2=80=99s competitive=
ness against China by reshoring semiconductor manufacturing and funding mor=
e scientific research. An earlier version of the bill was explicit in its n=
ame: United States Innovation and Competition Act. But wait, there=E2=80=99=
s more=E2=80=A6=20
(2) Machin=E2=80=99s Latest Shocker: A $700B Deal [https://substack.com/red=
irect/e28d71e2-aca9-4c1a-9676-0a8c24377c3b?u=3D16283549]=20
Burgess Everett [https://substack.com/redirect/a8a8cdef-b9cd-496d-8a21-2c05=
361b3a97?u=3D16283549] and Marianne Levine [https://substack.com/redirect/b=
4ed049c-d287-4068-831c-248ad6fa8c11?u=3D16283549] for Politico
The Manchin-Schumer deal includes roughly $370 billion in energy and climat=
e spending, $300 billion in deficit reduction, three years of subsidies for=
 Affordable Care Act premiums, prescription drug reform and significant tax=
 changes.
I=E2=80=99m sorry for doing back-to-back US legislation deals, but this is =
major! A few days after I wrote about how everyone was talking past each ot=
her [https://substack.com/redirect/bf3dd680-b3d7-40b7-8ce2-9eb9ee223968?u=
=3D16283549], and a week after I shared an Op-Ed titled =E2=80=9CWhat Joe M=
anchin Cost Us [https://substack.com/redirect/589af002-b1b2-4b1c-968c-44cc4=
eec34fb?u=3D16283549],=E2=80=9D members of the US government were able to a=
gree on not one, but two, big deals that include a lot of the kinds of thin=
gs we like over here at Not Boring.
In deal #2, Manchin and Chuck Schumer agreed on the Inflation Reduction Act=
 of 2022, which includes $370 billion in energy and climate spending that c=
ould, as Green Vortex coiner Robinson Meyer points out, get the US a very n=
ice 69.69% of the way to meeting the 2030 climate goal. It still needs to p=
ass the Senate and House.
In a side deal, Manchin, Schumer, and legendary day-trader Nancy Pelosi are=
 working on advancing permitting reforms, which could make it easier to gre=
enlight energy projects.=20
Overall, this seems like a big win for energy abundance if it=E2=80=99s pas=
sed, and further proof that compromise might not be dead.=20
More details and analysis from Meyer here [https://substack.com/redirect/5f=
921b2f-49b0-4252-947e-88b48dbcc868?u=3D16283549].
(3) AlphaFold reveals the structure of the protein universe [https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/1343906c-3ce6-400f-b8f3-2d4d94ab4598?u=3D16283549]
DeepMind Research Blog
AlphaFold has launched biology into an era of structural abundance, unlocki=
ng scientific exploration at digital speed. The AlphaFold DB serves as a =
=E2=80=98google search=E2=80=99 for protein structures, providing researche=
rs with instant access to predicted models of the proteins they're studying=
, enabling them to focus their effort and expedite experimental work. From =
fighting disease [https://substack.com/redirect/03c671d2-2728-400a-b5ef-0c9=
7de854a0e?u=3D16283549] to developing vaccines [https://substack.com/redire=
ct/78b8fd54-f241-42b3-8d67-67be1b1bcbeb?u=3D16283549], AlphaFold has alread=
y enabled incredible advances on some of our biggest global challenges.
Last year, AI lab DeepMind announced that its AlphaFold model has cracked o=
ne of the trickiest problems in biology: protein folding. Yesterday, DeepMi=
nd dropped an update: that it had =E2=80=9Cpredicted structures for nearly =
all catalogued proteins known to science, which will expand the AlphaFold D=
B [https://substack.com/redirect/935331f1-9586-48a2-a896-b6bb878cde56?u=3D1=
6283549] by over 200x - from nearly 1 million structures to over 200 millio=
n structures - with the potential to dramatically increase our understandin=
g of biology.=E2=80=9D=20
They open sourced the database, giving scientists and researchers free acce=
ss: find the full set at GitHub here [https://substack.com/redirect/a7b58b7=
a-8bae-461c-9330-f0f97a86c1c6?u=3D16283549]. No excuses: get out there and =
cure a disease this weekend.
For more, here=E2=80=99s a New Scientist thread on the implications [https:=
//substack.com/redirect/c73637bc-9706-4d9d-bfe1-e8dd5b4496f3?u=3D16283549].
(4) FIRST 100,000 KG REMOVED FROM THE GREAT PACIFIC GARBAGE PATCH [https://=
substack.com/redirect/97ba1940-52c3-476b-832c-c1c9de56fda8?u=3D16283549]
Boyan Slat [https://substack.com/redirect/17f10c4b-231f-417b-9d40-0ca4ac626=
a60?u=3D16283549], Founder & CEO of The Ocean Cleanup [https://substack.com=
/redirect/63d78102-9e33-44f6-9787-36e64dd6ae2a?u=3D16283549]
Submission credit: Sam McAllister [https://substack.com/redirect/668dd8d9-d=
bdc-4ab4-9bed-b5fc1a65c586?u=3D16283549]
Since deployment in August 2021, System 002 (or =E2=80=9CJenny=E2=80=9D) ha=
s now collected 101,353 kg of plastic over 45 extractions, sweeping an area=
 of ocean of over 3000km2 =E2=80=93 comparable to the size of Luxembourg or=
 Rhode Island. =20
The Ocean Cleanup has removed over 100,000kg of plastic from the Great Paci=
fic Garbage Patch [https://substack.com/redirect/6a3f7b2e-0c5c-4cb8-93c8-12=
e3a9c8b817?u=3D16283549].=20
There=E2=80=99s a ways to go: the GPGP consists of 100 million kg of garbag=
e, much of it in the form of small microplastics, but the company said that=
 its System 03, which it=E2=80=99s rolling out shortly, may be able to coll=
ect garbage at a 10x higher rate.=20
(5) The Big Business of Burying Carbon [https://substack.com/redirect/162c6=
8bb-fed8-411b-bb52-2becd594d2a8?u=3D16283549]
Jeffrey Ball [https://substack.com/redirect/26fcc5f0-ccfc-4fee-a42a-668a820=
a7708?u=3D16283549] for WIRED=20
The idea is that major emitters will hoover up their own carbon waste, then=
 pay to have it compressed into liquid and injected back down, safely and p=
ermanently, into the same sorts of rocks it came from=E2=80=94carbon captur=
e and sequestration on a scale unprecedented around the globe, large enough=
 to put a real dent in climate change [https://substack.com/redirect/debafa=
1b-1f5a-4d36-b29e-c29e5cca313d?u=3D16283549].
This one is a great example of the academia-government-business partnership=
 of the kind Rahul [https://substack.com/redirect/b2a05b8c-4a58-4164-91ff-2=
fb5e292eb22?u=3D16283549] described in Making Moonshots [https://substack.c=
om/redirect/2a0caf5a-7dbe-430b-9d4c-1ca9d3aee114?u=3D16283549].=20
Academia: Tip Meckel at the University of Texas=E2=80=99 Bureau of Economic=
 Geology spent nearly 15 years mapping the Gulf region=E2=80=99s undergroun=
d rock to prove that it was a good place for carbon capture and sequestrati=
on, then =E2=80=9Cpublished an atlas of the Gulf Miocene layer, 74 pages of=
 intricate maps and tiny print.=E2=80=9D
Government: The next year, the US Government introduced a =E2=80=9Cnew subs=
idy, modeled broadly on ones for renewable energy, [that] gave developers a=
 credit topping out at $50 for every ton of waste carbon dioxide they captu=
red and geologically stored.=E2=80=9D=20
Business: That set off a race, including oil & gas companies and startups, =
to =E2=80=9Cprofit from mitigating the damage those hydrocarbons have wroug=
ht.=E2=80=9D A startup, Carbonvert, won the bid for the Texas General Land =
Office=E2=80=99s first injection rights. Now, they=E2=80=99re racing to =E2=
=80=9Csign up enough polluters to make the project economically viable.=E2=
=80=9D
It=E2=80=99s still early days, and Carbonvert and others still need to prov=
e they can capture and sequester carbon profitably at $50 per ton, but it=
=E2=80=99s a step in the right direction towards something that climate sci=
entists agree will be a big part of slowing climate change.
Bonus #1: Idea Machines [https://substack.com/redirect/10d063fb-ba66-43d6-a=
41f-fdd4acbdb9ae?u=3D16283549] by Nadia Asparouhova [https://substack.com/r=
edirect/ec6684bb-2828-4d2b-bc87-965f25ca9bbe?u=3D16283549]
If philanthropy is pluralistic =E2=80=93 and, like any idea marketplace, th=
at is one of its virtues =E2=80=93 then there is no single school of though=
t that can =E2=80=9Csolve=E2=80=9D complex social questions, because everyo=
ne has a different vision for the world. If you=E2=80=99re pro-pluralism in=
 startups, you should also be pro-pluralism in philanthropy.
Nadia=E2=80=99s essay introduces the concept of an Idea Machine: =E2=80=9Ca=
 network of operators, thinkers, and funders, centered around an ideology, =
that=E2=80=99s designed to turn ideas into outcomes.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s =
an early attempt at a playbook for forming and scaling Idea Machines to gen=
erate the kind of outcomes we write about here every Friday.=20
Examples include Effective Altruism [https://substack.com/redirect/1cee8ace=
-7054-4b9f-9005-e790cae8a39d?u=3D16283549], Schmidt Futures [https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/c9af541f-2b76-4ae2-9cbb-e92206438dfe?u=3D16283549], Bentois=
m [https://substack.com/redirect/ff46cee0-4a03-42d2-9e47-2b2d03782f58?u=3D1=
6283549], Public Goods Funding [https://substack.com/redirect/6e76e8a9-1fdf=
-4a29-b29d-40cfb3c9e326?u=3D16283549], Progress Studies [https://substack.c=
om/redirect/1e1a8922-1fb5-4079-9204-94c78b5d0da6?u=3D16283549], It=E2=80=99=
s Time to Build [https://substack.com/redirect/351b36d5-8631-4a34-89ca-b698=
befd23e2?u=3D16283549], and SBF=E2=80=99s Future Fund [https://substack.com=
/redirect/5bc13dd2-f3f2-4969-b52f-5ccf9f31c0cf?u=3D16283549].  =20
Bonus #2: Into the Dataverse [https://substack.com/redirect/afd484dd-bc4a-4=
f76-b055-ebecab71a219?u=3D16283549] by Mike Sena [https://substack.com/redi=
rect/fd686cdb-0725-4ac7-aa1c-72f8741b9edd?u=3D16283549] at Ceramic Networks=
=20
Our vision of the Metaverse will run on the Dataverse: a composable, web-sc=
ale data ecosystem=E2=80=94owned by everyone and no one. Developers will bu=
ild interchangeable interfaces and online experiences that directly interac=
t with the Dataverse and the composable data that lives there. The Datavers=
e will play arguably the most important role within the Metaverse: a shared=
, high-performance, always-available graph of all data created and used by =
all applications.=20
Ceramic [https://substack.com/redirect/483992f7-c393-47a7-a1bd-81654289bd51=
?u=3D16283549] (from Not Boring Capital portfolio company 3Box Labs) =E2=80=
=9Cis a decentralized data network that brings unlimited data composability=
 to Web3 applications.=E2=80=9D Their blog post on the Dataverse this week =
is one of the most clearly-written and compelling visions of the web3 futur=
e that I=E2=80=99m excited about. Instead of financialization, this vision =
is about composability and interoperability, and about a billion connected =
apps created by anyone and everyone.=20
Thanks to Dan [https://substack.com/redirect/c81fa176-a2fc-4448-ac07-f47b5e=
fef350?u=3D16283549] for editing, and to all of you who submitted optimisti=
c content!
Humans are pulling off some pretty incredible things every week. Whenever y=
ou find examples, share them here [https://substack.com/redirect/5ca527a1-5=
291-49f6-8eb3-6d9182d03309?u=3D16283549] and we=E2=80=99ll feature some in =
the newsletter.
Have a great weekend, and see you on Monday!
Packy

